-Normandie, France":"Normandy, France","Criquetot-l'Esneval, Seine-Maritime, Normandie, França":"Criquetot-l'Esneval, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Chevalier Robert I d Esneval , Seigneur de Criquetot was born in 1115. He married Helouise d'Avranches before 1150, in France. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1195, in Normandy, France, at the age of 80."},"et":{"1115–1195":"1115–1195","1116–Female":"1116–Surnud","1150–1242":"1150–1242","1161–1242":"1161–1242","1116":"1116","1115":"1115","aproximadamente 1150":"umbes 1150","1242":"1242","before 1150":"enne 1150","1195":"1195","1161":"1161","1150":"1150","Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France":"Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Cirquet Haute-Normandie, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Criquetot-l'Esneval, Seine-Maritime, Normandie, França":"Criquetot-l'Esneval, Seine-Maritime, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1115–1195":"1115–11